***Achievements in Competitive Programming by Junior Students***

It is well known that students of IUT have to complete their undergraduate(Consisting of 180+ credits) within 3 years and 10 months.

But still, with the amount of academic pressure, current students are doing really good in competitive programming.

Other than senior programmers like M Saiful Bari and Mohammad Abdullah Matin Khan, juniors are also doing really good.

4th semester student, Shadman Protik was part of the runner up team in the last national programming contest held in Daffodil International University. He also has 1750+ rating point in Codeforces.

Another student from 4th semester, Zubayet Zaman Zico has solved 300+ problems in Lightoj very recently as well as solved around 1500+ programming problems in different online judges. He is 3rd among Bangladeshis in Project Eular Contest at HackerRank as well as has around 1750 rating point in Codeforces.

4th semester student Bakhtiar Hasan is ranked no.1 in Bangladesh in Project Eular Contest at HackerRank.

Another student from 4th semester Mahfuz Alam has solved 200+ problems in lightoj. He is also ranked no.4 among Bangladeshis in Project Eular Contest at HackerRank.

It is also great to inform that even first year students are doing very good. Fahim Shahriar Shakkhor from first year has solved more than 1000 problems in online judges along with having 1800+ rating point in Codeforces. Some other students from 1st year are also doing very good.

Not only that students from CSE Department are doing good in Programming, even students from other departments are also doing programming. Rashed Abid from 6th semester (EEE) has already solved near 1000 problems in different online judges.

We expect that junior students will take part more in competitive programming and achieve much more glory for IUT.

Let us apply this theory of probability to the
Qur‚Äôan, and assume that a person has guessed
all the information that is mentioned in the
Qur‚Äôan which was unknown at that time. Let us
discuss the probability of all the guesses being
simultaneously correct.
At the time when the Qur‚Äôan was revealed,
people thought the world was flat, there are
several other options for the shape of the earth.
It could be triangular, it could be quadrangular,
pentagonal, hexagonal, heptagonal, octagonal,
spherical, etc. Lets assume there are about 30
different options for the shape of the earth. The
Qur‚Äôan rightly says it is spherical, if it was a
guess the chances of the guess being correct is
1/30.
The light of the moon can be its own light or a
reflected light. The Qur‚Äôan rightly says it is a
reflected light. If it is a guess, the chances that
it will be correct is 1/2 and the probability that
both the guesses i.e the earth is spherical and
the light of the moon is reflected light is 1/30 x
1/2 = 1/60.
Further, the Qur‚Äôan also mentions every living
thing is made of water. Every living thing can
be made up of either wood, stone, copper,
aluminum, steel, silver, gold, oxygen, nitrogen,
hydrogen, oil, water, cement, concrete, etc. The
options are say about 10,000. The Qur‚Äôan
rightly says that everything is made up of
water. If it is a guess, the chances that it will
be correct is 1/10,000 and the probability of all
the three guesses i.e. the earth is spherical,
light of moon is reflected light and everything is
created from water being correct is 1/30 x 1/2
x 1/10,000 = 1/60,000 which is equal to
about .0017%.
The Qur‚Äôan speaks about hundreds of things
that were not known to men at the time of its
revelation. Only in three options the result
is .0017%. I leave it upto you, to work out the
probability if all the hundreds of the unknown
facts were guesses, the chances of all of them
being correct guesses simultaneously and there
being not a single wrong guess. It is beyond
human capacity to make all correct guesses
without a single mistake, which itself is
sufficient to prove to a logical person that the
origin of the Qur‚Äôan is Divine.--Dr.Zakir Naik

Sahih Bukhari

Volume 1, Book 3, Number 56:

Narrated Abu Huraira:

While the Prophet was saying something in a gathering, a Bedouin came and asked him, When would the Hour (Doomsday) take place? Allah's Apostle continued his talk, so some people said that Allah's Apostle had heard the question, but did not like what that Bedouin had asked. Some of them said that Alllah's Apostle had not heard it. When the Prophet finished his speech, he said, Where is the questioner, who enquired about the Hour (Doomsday)? The Bedouin said, I am here, O Allah's Apostle. Then the Prophet said, When honesty is lost, then wait for the Hour (Doomsday). The Bedouin said, How will that be lost? The Prophet said, When the power or authority comes in the hands of unfit persons, then wait for the Hour (Doomsday.)

For those who have been asking what resources did I use for the writing module I'm providing the materials for you all here.

1) Vocabulary:  
    https://www.ielts-mentor.com/ielts-vocabulary
    http://ieltsliz.com/vocabulary/
    https://www.ieltsadvantage.com/vocabulary/
    https://www.thesaurus.com/
2) Sentence structure and grammar:                 
    https://www.youtube.com/user/EnglishTeacherEmma/videos
    https://www.youtube.com/user/JamesESL
    Barron's writing for the IELTS (only grammar portion) 
3) Sample essay and essay structures: 
    https://www.ielts-mentor.com/writing-sample/writing-task-2 
    http://ielts-simon.com/ielts-help-and-english-pr/ielts-writing-task-2/
  https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCglDIsg_Z9mE2oT9hsrbzFA
http://www.ielts-practice.org/band-9-essays/ 
Most importantly Cambridge consult books and Dr smart IELTS. 

Task 1: 
http://ielts-up.com/writing/ielts-academic-task-1.html
          https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCRSFsZwTpcm2IZKcWTOyyZg

The books mentioned above are on my google drive link: https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1LeecPB9C217f0ibxrRAvUzqU9JuX7Oh3

Notes: # I took help from many of my seniors,juniors and friends who previously scored well and I was under direct supervision of one of my senior brothers from cadet college, took feedback from them and tried to improve my weak points.
           # In case of vocabularies focus more on topic related words than so called unique or uncommon or tougher words and be sure of the collocations. Check the spelling mistakes. Be careful in using linking words, use them but not in excess and unnecessarily. 
          # Use relevant examples!!! 
          # Use more complex sentences with some simple and compound sentences and make sure your grammar is alright. 
          # Read samples! read samples!! Read samples!!! and practice! 
         # Plan the essay beforehand, take minimum 5-7 minutes to plan and organize your thoughts, note them down! It will save your time! 
         # Revise the whole essay for at least once! 

N.B: These are no professional advice, rather sharing my experience (which you might ignore).

I am an engineering student. I have a mathematics course in my fourth semester. My teacher has been teaching for twelve years. Seems standard, right? The man made a mistake. How do I know it was a mistake? Common sense, that's how. It was pointed out in class - our arguments were rejected, of course. Over the course of about ten minutes, I learnt that he was equally adept at logical discourse as he was at flying. And today, on my midterms, I wrote what I know to be wrong because it was what my teacher knows to be right. When someone with a PhD is incapable of stringing two coherent sentences together in the working language of the course, that should be significant enough of a red flag for him not to get hired, right? Guess not.

I can tell you exactly what happened here. This happened in a business park located in Rye Canyon in Santa Clarita, California. 

During a car show that Paul was using to support his charity Reach Out Worldwide, Paul and Roger (The Owner) of Always Evolving Performance, where the event was held decided to take a spin.

They left the AEP parking lot turning right onto Alta Vista Ave. They then turned right onto Constellation Rd, and then right again onto Kelly Johnson Pkwy where the driver began testing the limits of the Porsche.

Kelly Johnson Pkwy has a small s curve and a wide sweeping right turn that turns into Hercules St. Paul and Roger's speed was too fast into the curve and the car's rear end kicked out toward the driver side. The driver then over corrected and the passenger side rear end kicked out to the passenger side.

Sliding sideways at high speed, the car hit a light pole directly on the passenger door where Paul was sitting and the car was split/wrapped around the pole. The car then came to a sliding stop on a small tree where it then caught fire.

You can Google "Hercules St, Valencia California" and then select street view. You can then follow the path I've described above and see their final path and exactly what I've narrated.

Hopefully this puts the speculation to rest. Today the automotive community lost two great ambassadors.

Too often we tell ourselves we aren't  smart enough or attractive enough or talented enough to pursue our dreams. We buy into what others say about us, or we put restrictions on ourselves. What's worse is that when you consider yourself unworthy, you are putting limits on how God can work through you!
When you give up on your dreams, you put God in a box. After all, you are His creation. He made you for a purpose. Therefore your life cannot be limited any more than God's love can be contained. I have a choice. You have a choice. We can choose to dwell on disappointments and shortcomings. We can choose to be bitter, angry, or sad. Or when faced with hard times and hurtful people, we can choose to learn from the experience and move forward, taking responsibility for our own happiness. As God's child, you are beautiful and precious, worth more than all the diamonds in the world. You and I are perfectly suited to be who we were meant to be! Even still, it should always be our goal to become an even better person and stretch our boundaries by dreaming big. Adjustments are necessary along the way because life isn't always rosy, but it is always worth living. I'm here to tell you that no matter what your circumstances may be, as long as you are breathing, you have a contribution to make.

#life_without_limits

FINANCIAL AID FOR JANUARY & MAY 2014 A'LEVEL ACCOUNTING (UNIT:2) COURSE.

Vertical Horizon is honored to announce financial aid for highest mark achiever in Accounting (Unit 1). We show our gratitude by helping this students to do much better result under extensive guidance of our course instructor Tawsif Alam Khan. It is our pride to provide best educational facilities to such talents without charging any fees. We believe its you and those respected parents who deserve such respects from us. 

FINANCIAL AID SCHEMES: 
* Students achieving 300 straight will be provided with 100% financial Aid. (No course fees will be applied).
* Students achieving 290 above will be provided with 67% financial aid. (2000 BDT monthly fees).
* Students achieving 280 above will be provided with 84% financial aid (2500 BDT monthly fees).
* Regular Course fees 3000 BDT (only Unit 2) and 6000 BDT (both Unit 1 & Unit 2) for other students. No admission fees is applied for admission in Unit 2 batch.

HOW TO APPLY FOR JANUARY 2014 BATCH:
* Students applicable for financial aid have to submit financial aid form and photocopy of valid documents as proof of the marks they achieved in Unit 1 by 24 August 2013.
* Current students must have all their regular fees cleared till the month of August 2013. 
* Only new admission is accepted for those who deserve financial aid. 30 August 2013 is the last date of admission for new students in current batch. So far PLC and Share Issue chapter are completed and extra classes will be provided to new students at the end of October 2013, to cover those two chapters. 
* Financial Aid will be applicable for September 2013 onwards.

HOW TO APPLY FOR MAY 2014 BATCH: 
* Students applicable for financial aid have to submit financial aid form and photocopy of valid documents as a proof of the marks achieved during admission. 
* Last date of Registration 10 September 2013. 
* Classes will start from second week of September 2013. 
* Financial aid will be applicable from first day of class starting September 2013.

TERMS & CONDITION FOR FINANCIAL AID: 
* Students have to maintain 90% attendance. 
* Students wont be allowed to join any other instructor for A'level Accounting Unit 2. 
* Students have to maintain honorable grade (min 60%) in all Mock Examination. 
* Students must not get involved in any unethical activities during this course period.
* Dept Administration holds the complete right to redeem financial aid for violating the above terms and conditions.

For further details contact dept administration : Tawsif Alam Khan + 88 01729292952 or Fahim Uz Zaman + 88 01688942000.

Regards VH ACCOUNTING DEPT

If you're an upcoming writer and wondering about where you can get a platform to showcase your talents, this is it.

Who dreamt of this day?
A 7-year-old kid reading Tin Goyenda books and telling himself, "Someday, I'll write like this too!"
Or the 9-year-old boy who had just written a story about werewolves and was too scared to show it to anyone, thinking that they might laugh at him.
Or the 15-year-old teenager, who promised himself that he'll become a published writer someday, no matter how hard he has to work for it.
Or the 20-year-old daydreamer, who lived in an imaginary world, making up those weird short stories.
No matter how many of my stories are featured in this, this is my book and this is my life <3

Creepy crawlies,

Careful there she says,
Untold, unknown,
The demon of darkness there stays.

Happy Mother's day Maa.

To one of the few women who made me the kickass sonuvagun I am today,
To the powerhouse that never seems to tire,
To the amazing chef always welcoming me with food fit for gods,
To the one who built me to be the emotional rock that I am by virtue of her tough love principles,
To the patient (read: usually impatient) and incredibly tolerant woman dealing with my crap for the entirety of my time here,
To the woman responsible for my time here,
To the amazing person who is all of the above,
To the glue keeping the family tight,
To Ammu,

You are more of a gift to me than you think I am to you. Always and forever. In case I don't say it enough, you're the best mother one can ask for. I wish I could be your idea of perfect, and I try my best, but to err is human. One day, In Sha Allah, you will have all you want of me. And that'll be the pinnacle of success for me.

You can't be outdone, outshone.

Always look up to you regardless of how tall I grow. 

Love you more than I show.

Happy Mother's Day, Ammu. Tomake cchaara jibon bhaaba jay na.

With loads of love,
Your favourite child,
Shomoy moto lokkhi shona, shomoy furale iblisher pona,
Dipush.

Dear parents of children applying to universities here particularly ones that test you on the HSC syllabus, this is just a gentle reminder.

It is NOT OKAY to belittle your children because they couldn't get in to a presumably excellent institution for their undergrad. Especially if they, like myself, are coming from an entirely different academic background. It is NOT OKAY to tell your children that they are useless if they couldn't get in while a few of their friends could. 

Let us consider a simple example. Suppose you're an ENT specialist. And now you're given 3 months to learn about the heart entirely and enough to be able to successfully perform an open-heart surgery, whilst in a flight above Ukraine with guns on the ground ready to fire at you. You may be able to pull it off, but if you aren't, can you really be blamed? 

Don't blame us for not surviving a war that we weren't taught to fight to begin with. Some of us get lucky. Some of us don't. But we all try. At least the few I've talked to, who are in the same crap as myself. With all due respect, appreciate our efforts as much as you ask us to appreciate yours.

Peace.

Found this really cool. So, if you're into books, I am looking for people to participate in a large scale book exchange program. You could be anywhere in the world. "‡¶Æ‡¶æ‡¶á ‡¶¨‡ßü, ‡¶Ü‡¶≤‡ßç‡¶≤‡¶æ‡¶π‡ßç‚Äå‡¶∞ ‡¶ï‡¶æ‡¶õ‡ßá ‡¶¶‡¶æ‡ßü‡ßÄ ‡¶•‡¶æ‡¶ï‡¶¨‡ßá" - ‡¶∞‡ßá‡¶ú‡¶æ ‡¶∏‡ßç‡¶Ø‡¶æ‡¶∞ (Dept. of Mathematics, Notre Dame College)

The country plunges further into darkness each day. What saddens me is that 90% students taking board exams expect getting questions beforehand. Why?
If you are taking an exam why would you expect a question leak? Why would you search for it, buy it, spread it, even look at it? Our education system is possibly the worst one, but why do you have to be dishonest, corrupt? 
Your parents, your teachers, shaped you into the person you are today, they tried to teach you all the best values and ideals there can be. How can you stain their names for a few marks? What remains the difference between an uneducated person and you if you can't stand up against those very people when they force you to cheat?
Why should all the lessons, all the education of 10 or 12 years go in vain? "‡¶∏‡¶¨‡¶æ‡¶á ‡¶§‡ßã ‡¶®‡ßá‡ßü" can never be an excuse, you should do as your conscience says, if you have any.
Allah is watching, and you will surely face judgement at His will. Even if you are an atheist, karma is a bitch. üòÇ
You may joke about it like "‡¶ï‡ßã‡¶∂‡ßç‡¶ö‡ßá‡¶®‡¶ü‡¶æ ‡¶™‡¶æ‡¶á‡¶≤‡ßá ‡¶ú‡ßã‡¶∏ ‡¶π‡¶á‡¶§" but let this be the end of that.
You will feel severe crisis of self-respect someday. 
What is the point of getting 90 being corrupt? I would be happy scoring 70-80 of my own accord. Even asking your friends for answers is wrong, but nothing compares to the question issue.
Things that are wrong can never get you success, don't sell yourself out. Stick to your ideals, stick to what is right, you will surely get its reward. 
‡¶¨‡¶æ‡¶ü‡¶™‡¶æ‡¶∞‡¶ø ‡¶ï‡¶∞‡ßá ‡¶≠‡¶æ‡¶≤‡ßã ‡¶ï‡¶∞‡¶≤‡ßá ‡¶è‡¶ï‡¶¶‡¶ø‡¶® ‡¶ß‡¶∞‡¶æ ‡¶ñ‡¶æ‡¶¨‡¶æ ;) While you cheat and selfishly get marks you don't deserve, you deprive a hard working student who decided to remain honest from being able to sit for an exam that he worked hard for.

We need to understand that getting 90+ is not worth selling out our values. If our parents and teachers force us to get good marks even if we don't deserve that, we need to correct them, not indulge in corruption. Marks won't even get us jobs, if we don't have skills. And if we want to be businessmen, artists, musicians, or anything else, we don't need good marks. For once we need to follow the path we dream of, with dignity. It is time we stopped being their puppets.

üëè Year Review üëè

Ah, 2017 - the sequel to 2016 that nobody asked for. The first half went by pretty smoothly, but the second half was pretty rough, and culminated in one of the worst things I've ever experienced. However, I was determined not to let it change me, and December 2017 was arguably one of the best months in my life, thanks to some very special people whom I will be grateful to forever.

This was the year I reconnected with old friends, made new ones, lost some, and found out which ones really matter. This was also the year where I somehow made a comeback academically despite all the shit I had going on.

I don't really believe in resolutions but if I had to have one, it'd be to go into 2018 with a more positive outlook on life. Do I have regrets? Of course I do - I mean, who doesn't? But, they're a part of what makes me who I am today, and if I could do it all again, I wouldn't change a thing.

Regarding the matter of posts disappearing from people's timelines and people noticing unusual activities in their facebook accounts, including logins from unidentified devices as suggested in the photo attached:

A Facebook account normally is attached to a cell phone number and government has access to all telecom number in Bangladesh. Now Government Intelligence agency (DGFI and NSI) can access all the telecom and they are using masking technology to access the phone's text message. By using the option of "Forget My Password" -> Send a Text to Reset Password -> They are changing password getting into account and deleting stuff. Later they keeping all active session on so that facebook user can log into his/her account without using password as they don't want to get caught by facebook.

How to fix this problem:

1. Take off your phone number from facebook. (Settings>Mobile>Remove)
2. Use only Gmail or Hotmail email address in recovery option.
3. Download Google Voice app on your cell phone and Create a new virtual number and then use it as a recovery option. Bangladesh Government has no access to Google data.
4. At the end Change your password and logout from all active session. (Settings>Security and Login>Change Password>Log out of all sessions)

Make sure you take off your cell phone number from your email address as well. Two-step verification is not safe for Bangladesh.

Went to Saint Martin's Island for a day. The scenery I enjoyed was worth all the tiresome journey I had. The beauty of the Bay of Bengal will always be engraved in my mind. The thing I witnessed that broke my heart was the way we are destroying Bay of Bengal. Today was the only day I felt ashamed of being a Bangladeshi. The number of chips' packs, cold drink cans and plastic cups that were thrown into the sea was probably uncountable, not to mention the number of times I have seen people spit into the sea. None of us can change things on our own. Lets start from our families. Lets keep the beautiful things beautiful. Lets not ruin nature anymore.

On July 07,2015 I received a text saying my migration to Adamjee Cantonment College was successful. I was neither happy nor sad about the news. On July 26,2015 I attended my first class at the college. And now I'm here standing in my college campus and wondering how time flew away. Leaving Chittagong and coming to Dhaka for studying was one of the saddest things for me at that time. I never thought of getting such mentors, teachers, friends and most of all memories out of my college life back then. This was probably two of my best years in this small life I have already lived. 
Adamjee Cantonment College gave me the opportunity to see a leader like Tameem Ahmed Chowdhury sir. I will always remember this man for making the college a whole lot better and enjoyable place for us the Adamjeeans. 
Adamjee Cantonment College gave me teachers like Zakia Sultana ma'am to whom I can look upto for every problem I face. 
Adamjee Cantonment College gave me the opportunity to spend times with so many wonderful people whom I call my "FRIENDS". 
Adamjee Cantonment College gave me some awesome seniors who will always be ready to help their juniors with whatever they can.
Adamjee Cantonment College gave me so many memories that I will cherish throughout my life.
Adamjee Cantonment College gave me a family which people know as a club. Adamjee Cantonment College Photography Club - ACCPC is my family <3 I will miss working. 
Last but not least Adamjee Cantonment College gave me a motto to follow and make world a better place. I pray and intend to build my life based on the motto "EDUCATION DISCIPLINE MORALITY".
#proud_to_be_an_adamjeean
